In addition to a linear relationship between the dependent and independent variables, linear regression model assumes that the residuals are independent, have constant variance, and are normally distributed. Residuals are leftover of the dependent variable after fitting a model (independent variables) to data and they could reveal unexplained patterns in the data by the fitted model. Patterns in residuals can be explored with diagnostic plots.

# create a regression model
mymod <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = learn)

# draw diagnostic plots using the plot() function
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(mymod)

# Note: intentional deviation from exercise instructions
# To produce plots 1, 2 and 5 only, use argument which = c(1,2,5)

Residuals vs Fitted plot shows if residuals have non-linear patterns. Here, cases are distributed quite equally around the horizontal line and no obvious pattern can be detected.

Normal Q-Q plot helps to assess whether residuals are normally distributed. Here, the points appear to skew away from the straight line especially at the lower tail meaning that residuals are not normally distributed. Cases #145, #35 and #56 should be explored further as they have standardized residuals below -3.

Scale-Location plot can be used to check the assumption of constant variance. Here, the residuals appear randomly spread along a horizontal line confirming the assumption.

Residuals vs Leverage plot helps to identify influential cases in the data. Here, Cook’s distance lines (red dashed lines) are not even visible, meaning that all cases are well within Cook’s distance and not influential to the regression results.

I’d expect students with lots of freetime after school to consume more alcohol than students on average. On the other hand, high_use of alcohol might relate with lower final grades. I’m interested to learn about the differences between the age groups (under/legal age) as well as between the sexes in this context.

3.3 Model fitting with multiple predictor variables

By specifying a binomial error distribution with the function glm() I can fit a logistic regression model to predict the probability of a student’s high_use of alcohol (a binary outcome) with variables freetime (numeric), sex (binary), under_age (binary) and G3 (numeric).

Note1: female sexF and under_ageFALSE are set as the reference group for the predictor factors.

Note2: as an afterthought, freetimeis actually an ordered categorical variable but I’ve opted to treat it as continuous (with linear effects) here.

# define a new column
alc_age <- mutate(alc, under_age = age < 18)

# fit a model with glm()
m1 <- glm(high_use ~ freetime + sex + under_age + G3, data = alc_age, family = "binomial")

# print out a summary of the model
summary(m1)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = high_use ~ freetime + sex + under_age + G3, family = "binomial", 
##     data = alc_age)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -1.4085  -0.8563  -0.6645   1.2037   2.1104  
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)   
## (Intercept)   -1.08898    0.58247  -1.870  0.06154 . 
## freetime       0.26527    0.12262   2.163  0.03052 * 
## sexM           0.77881    0.23785   3.274  0.00106 **
## under_ageTRUE -0.17279    0.26788  -0.645  0.51891   
## G3            -0.08127    0.03543  -2.293  0.02182 * 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 465.68  on 381  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 439.48  on 377  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 449.48
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4

Each estimated coefficient in the summary above is the expected change in the log odds of high_use for a unit increase in the corresponding predictor variable holding the other predictor variables constant at certain value.

From the estimates of the coefficients, I can see that freetime and male gender sexM influence high_use positively while final grades G3 and age group under_ageTRUE have a negative effect. The coefficient of under_ageTRUE is not significant (p > 0.05), while the coefficients of freetime, sexM and G3 are significant.

Deviance is a measure for goodness of fit in glm. Null deviance is the goodness for a model fitted with only the intercept. Adding the four independent variables to the model decreased the (residual) deviance by 26.2 points with loss of 4 degrees of freedom. Lower score means a better fit.

Akaike information criteria AIC is a measure for the quality of the model based on deviance (but it also penalizes more complicated models). It can only be interpreted when comparing models (lower is better), otherwise the number has no meaning.

Fisher scoring tells that the algorithm needed 4 iterations to perform the fit, indicating only that the model did converge and not telling anything more about the model or the goodness of its fit.

Now, if I refit the model by removing the least influential variable under_age, I can use the residual deviance and AIC scores to compare the models.

# refit the model with glm()
m2 <- glm(high_use ~ freetime + sex + G3, data = alc, family = "binomial")

# print out a summary of the model
summary(m2)

Removing the variable doesn’t improve residual deviance but the refitted model gets a lower (better) AIC scores. I think it’s fair to conclude at this point that whether students were under or of the legal age (18) does not significantly affect the odds of being in the high_use group and I can reject my hypothesis regarding this relationship.

In logistic regression, the outcome variable by itself does not have a linear relationship with the predictor variables but its logit transformation does.

Odds ratios are simply the exponentiated coefficients from the logit model. The 95% confidence interval around the odds ratios are the exponentiated 95% confidence intervals from the logit model. Using tidy() function from broom package I can produce a table with the results in terms of odds ratios including their confidence interval.

m2 %>%
  tidy(exponentiate = T, conf.int = T) %>%
  mutate_if(is.numeric, ~ round(.,2)) %>%
  kable(align = c("l", rep("c", 6)))
term estimate std.error statistic p.value conf.low conf.high
(Intercept) 0.31 0.57 -2.03 0.04 0.10 0.95
freetime 1.30 0.12 2.13 0.03 1.02 1.66
sexM 2.19 0.24 3.29 0.00 1.38 3.50
G3 0.92 0.03 -2.44 0.01 0.86 0.98

So, my fitted model says that, holding freetime and grades G3 at a fixed value, the odds ratio of being the group high_use of alcohol for male sexM students is 2.19, i.e. the odds for male students are 119% higher than for female students. Holding sex and grades G3 at a fixed value, a one-unit increase in freetime increases the odds of being in the high_use group by 30%. And holding sex and freetime at a fixed value, a one-unit increase in final grades G3 decreases the odds of being in the high_use` group by 8%.

It looks like my hypothesis that more freetime increases the odds of high_use of alcohol is confirmed, as is the hypothesis regarding a negative relationship between final grades G3 and high_use.

3.4 Predictions

The model goodness of fit can also be evaluated based on the difference between the observed and predicted data. I’ve crosstabulated the observed values for high_use against the values predicted by my model. The crosstab shows how many observations of high_use my model predicts correctly (FALSE/FALSE and TRUE/TRUE) as well as those it predicts incorrectly.

# predict() the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(m2, type = "response")

# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc'
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

# tabulate the target variable versus the predictions
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   259    9
##    TRUE    100   14

The model accuracy can be calculated as the percentage of values predicted correctly. The accuracy of my model is 71.5%.

3.5 Cross validation

# define a loss function (average prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2984293
# K-fold cross-validation
library(boot)
cv <- cv.glm(data = alc, cost = loss_func, glmfit = m2, K = 10)

# average number of wrong predictions in the cross validation
cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2984293

4.1 Boston MASS data exploration

# access libraries
library(MASS); library(factoextra); library(corrplot); library(tidyr); library(dplyr); library(ggplot2); library(GGally); library(summarytools); library(knitr)
# load data 
data(Boston)

The Boston dataset from the MASS R package contains information regarding different areas in the city of Boston. This dataset with 506 cases (rows) contains information collected by the U.S Census Service concerning housing in the area of Boston Mass. The data was originally published by Harrison, D. and Rubinfeld, D.L. 1978. Hedonic prices and the demand for clean air. J. Environ. Economics & Management (5), 81-102.

There are 14 variables (columns) in the dataset. The variables are:
- crim: per capita crime rate by town
- zn: proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft
- indus: proportion of non-retail business acres per town
- chas: Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)
- nox: nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)
- rm: average number of rooms per dwelling
- age: proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940
- dis: weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centers
- rad: index of accessibility to radial highways
- tax: full-value property-tax rate per $10,000
- ptratio: pupil-teacher ratio by town
- black: 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town
- lstat: lower status of the population (percent)
- medv: median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s

To show summaries of the variables, I wanted to try dfSummary() function from summarytools package. It provides this really neat html output with basic descriptive statistics (or values for categorical variables) and simple histograms or bar plots according to data type. IQR = interquartile range, CV = coefficient of variance. There are no missing cases nor dublicates, and the variables are numeric except chas and rad which are integers.

# summary statistics
print(dfSummary(Boston), method = "render", plain.ascii = FALSE, style = "grid", varnumbers = FALSE, valid.col = FALSE)

Prior probabilities of groups reflect the proportion of each group in the training dataset. Group means are the average values of each of the variables for each group. Coefficients of linear discriminants provide the linear combination of variables that are used to form the LDA decision rule. Because there are 4 groups, there are 4–1 linear discriminants (LD). For each LD, there is one coefficient corresponding to each of the variables. Proportion of the trace gives the variance explained by each LD function. Here, LD1 explains 96% of the variance, with the remainder explained by LD2 and LD3.

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "orange", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}
# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)
# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 2)

# predict classes with test data
lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)
# cross tabulate the results
acc <- table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)
acc
##           predicted
## correct    low med_low med_high high
##   low       18       8        1    0
##   med_low    8      16        3    0
##   med_high   1      10       16    1
##   high       0       0        0   20

If the classification was perfect, all cases would fall on the crosstab diagonal and all off-diagonal values would be zeroes. The overall predictive accuracy of LDA can be calculated from the proportion of cases that lie along the diagonal. Here, the overall accuracy is 60%.

sum(acc[row(acc) == col(acc)]) / sum(acc) 
## [1] 0.6862745

4.4 K-means clustering

K-means clustering is an unsupervised machine learning algorithm. It looks for patterns in an unlabeled dataset with minimum human supervision and tries to group similar kinds of items to form clusters. The algorithm aims to maximize the intra-class similarity and minimize the inter-class similarity. The k represents the number of clusters predefined by the analyst.

Data preparation

# reload data
data(Boston)
# standardize data
bn_scal2 <- scale(Boston)
# coerce as dataframe
bn_scal2 <- as.data.frame(bn_scal2)

Understand distance metrics

Euclidean distance is the shortest distance between two points. The k-means algorithm uses this metric to measure the distance (similarity or dissimilarity) between data points.

# euclidean distance matrix
dist_eu <- dist(bn_scal2)
# look at the summary of the distances
summary(dist_eu)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.1343  3.4625  4.8241  4.9111  6.1863 14.3970

Manhattan distance is also known as the city block distance. It’s the sum of absolute differences between points across all the dimensions.

# manhattan distance matrix
dist_man <- dist(bn_scal2, method = 'manhattan')
# look at the summary of the distances
summary(dist_man)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.2662  8.4832 12.6090 13.5488 17.7568 48.8618

K-means algorithm

K-means can be computed with the kmeans() function. The number of clusters (k) is set with the argument centers, and the option nstart attempts multiple initial configurations and reports on the best one. But before running the algorithm, the optimal number k must be determined.

In order to find the optimal number of clusters, the Elbow method is used here. The method looks at the total within-cluster sum of square (WSS) as a function of the number of clusters. I’m using the factoextra::fviz_nbclust() function which has the Elbow method nicely wrapped up as a single function.

# set seed to get a reproducible random result
set.seed(123)
# Elbow method
fviz_nbclust(bn_scal2, kmeans, method = "wss")

The optimal number of clusters appears at the bend in the elbow. Here the Elbow method is a bit ambiguous: is the bend at k = 2 or higher? Just to check I’ll use another method called Silhouette which is also easily available via the fviz_nbclust() function.

# set seed to get a reproducible random result
set.seed(123)
# Sihouette method
fviz_nbclust(bn_scal2, kmeans, method = "silhouette")

Based on the Silhouette method, the optimal number of clusters k = 2, which I’ll enter as centers = 2 argument to run the k-means algorithm. I’ll use the fviz_cluster() function to plot the clusters. This function performs principal component analysis to represent the variables in a two-dimensional plane.

# set seed to get a reproducible random result
set.seed(123)
# run k-means algorithm
k2 <- kmeans(bn_scal2, centers = 2, nstart = 25)
# visualize using PCA
fviz_cluster(k2, bn_scal2, ellipse.type = "norm")

The descriptive statistics table includes both measures of central tendency (values) and measures of dispersion (variability) for each variable. Here, these measures show that the dataset contains only non-negative values. The geometric means of the variables range between 13 (EDS) and 149 (MMR) but the medians are much closer together, between 13 (GNIpc) and 74 (LE).

This already tells something about data distribution (which I’ll later explore visually in more detail), namely, when mean and median are quite different, the data is skewed. The variables also have very different data ranges as well as standard deviance, both of which are measures indicating the spread of data. This is reflected in the measure CV (coefficient of variation) which is a standardized measure for relative variability.

The table also provides information about data validity and completeness. Of course, having completed the data wrangling part of this exercise, which included removal of rows with missing values as instructed, it’s no surprise there are no missing values.

Distributions

Distributions of multiple variables can be compared by wrapping boxplots together using e.g. chart.Boxplot() function which is from the same package PerformanceAnalytics as the very useful chart.Correlation() I’ll also use for a graphical overview of the data.

# boxplots of all variables in a wrapper

# boxplots of variables excluding 'MMR', 'GNIpc' and 'ABR'

The above boxplot chart on the left reveals that:
- MMR and GNIpc have by far the widest ranges
- they are also heavily skewed to the right and
- have quite a few outliers (i.e. value points more than 1.5 times the IQR from the box edges)
- also ABR is heavily right-skewed and has a relatively wide range.

Because variables in this dataset have such different ranges, it’s actually best to plot variables with more compact ranges separately (see plot on the right above). Now the boxplots can be interpreted e.g. as follows:
- LE is somewhat skewed to the left and PR to the right
- SE_f is spread more evenly than the other variables, i.e. has a longer box (IQR)
- EDS and likely LFPR_f too, are normally distributed.

Correlations

This graph output by chart.Correlation() not only illustrates the correlation matrix but also outputs histograms and scatterplots with fitted lines for each variable in a visually informative package. Because of the histograms (on the diagonal) this graph alone might be sufficient to explore distributions as well as correlations. The bivariate scatterplots (on the bottom of the diagonal) are a nice addition and allow for interpretation of any potentially non-linear patterns in the relationships.

# correlation matrix plotted with histograms
chart.Correlation(human, histogram = TRUE, pch=19)

On top of the diagonal, the numbers are Pearson correlation coefficients describing the strength of the relationship between each pair of variables. The stars indicate p-values, i.e. the significance of the relationship. Th strongest, statistically significant correlation is between LE and MMR. In fact, there’s a group of variables (LE, EDS, MMR, ABR and SE) that seem quite strongly interrelated having either negative or positive correlations. GNIpc has only weak correlations, most significantly with MMR and ABR. The same can be said about LFPR_f. PR on the other hand, does not correlate much at all with the other variables.

5.2 PCA with non-standardized data

This dataset with 8 variables is multidimensional making it a challenge to interpret the data. The dimensions can be reduced and the principal components (i.e. linear combinations or mixtures of the initial variables) can be identified using the PCA method. According to DataCamp (Helsinki ODS Course) the preferred base r function for PCA is prcomp which uses SVD (Singular Value Decomposition) method. It decomposes the data matrix into a product of smaller matrices, which extract the underlying principal components.

First, I’ll perform PCA with non-standardized data.

# perform principal component analysis (with the SVD method)
pca_human <- prcomp(human)

# summary of pca_human
s<- summary(pca_human)

# rounded % of variance captured by each PC
pca_pr <- round(100*s$importance[2,], digits = 1) 

# print out % of variance
pca_pr
##  PC1  PC2  PC3  PC4  PC5  PC6  PC7  PC8 
## 76.2 21.6  1.1  0.6  0.3  0.2  0.0  0.0
# create object pc_lab to be used as axis labels
pc_lab <- paste0(names(pca_pr), " (", pca_pr, "%)")

# draw a biplot
biplot(pca_human, cex = c(0.8, 1), col = c("grey40", "deeppink2"), xlab = pc_lab[1], ylab = pc_lab[2])

FIGURE 5.2 PCA on dataset with non-standardized variables measuring gender inequality and human development in 155 countries. The most dispersed variables Maternal Mortality Rate (MMR) and Gross National Income per capita (GNIpc) appear to contribute most to PC1 and PC2, respectively.

5.3 PCA with standardized data

Now, PCA is performed with standardized data. And indeed, as expected: the results are quite different from the first attempt with non-standardized data.

# standardize the variables
human_std <- scale(human)

# perform principal component analysis (with the SVD method)
pca_human <- prcomp(human_std)

# summary of pca_human
s<- summary(pca_human)

# rounded % of variance captured by each PC
pca_pr <- round(100*s$importance[2,], digits = 1) 

# print out % of variance
pca_pr
##  PC1  PC2  PC3  PC4  PC5  PC6  PC7  PC8 
## 53.0 15.6 11.4  8.8  3.8  3.5  2.6  1.3
# create object pc_lab to be used as axis labels
pc_lab <- paste0(names(pca_pr), " (", pca_pr, "%)")

# draw a biplot
biplot(pca_human, cex = c(0.8, 1), col = c("grey40", "deeppink2"), xlab = pc_lab[1], ylab = pc_lab[2])

FIGURE 5.3 PCA on dataset with standardized variables measuring gender inequality and human development in 155 countries.

The takeaway is clear: the results of PCA depend on the scaling of the variables. This can be avoided by standardization.

When the variables were not standardized (figure 5.2), PC1 explained 76.2% of the variation in the dataset and PC2 21.6%. The 97.8% rate of variance explained would be a great result if the analysis was performed with standardized variables. Here, the “most contributing” original variables GNIpc and MMR are actually, and simply, the most dispersed variables in the dataset.

If one wanted to interpret the PCA biplot (figure 5.2) anyway, the loading vectors of variables GNIpc and MMR appear only weakly correlated (angle between arrows closer to 90°). Because these variables have relatively speaking significantly higher variability than the other variables, their loading vectors require a scale (axes at the top and on the right in figure 5.3) were the other variables can not be distinguished. The vectors might be interpreted as MMR have the highest contribution to PC1 and GNIpc to PC2.

After standardization of the variables (figure 5.3), PC1 (53%) and PC2(15.6%) now explain a total 68.6% of the variation in the dataset. PCs 3 captures an additional 11.4% of the variation, so including PC 3 would increase the total amount of variance explained to 80% and that might be desirable depending on research goals. Yet, selecting only PCs 1 and 2 really gives PCA more power as what comes to reducing dimension.

With standardized data, the variable arrows are actually comparable with each other and the PCs. Let’s interpret the loading plot, i.e. the arrows (or vectors) showing the influence of each original variable on the PCs. Variables LE, SE_f and EDS are grouped close together, meaning that they have positive correlation. Similarly, ABR and MMR form another group with not much angle between them, again, indicating positive correlation. Both groups have pretty similar (high) scores on PC1, so these variables have about as much influence on PC1 - only to opposite directions, meaning that the groups are negatively correlated. Their contribution to PC2 is minimal, whereas variables PR and LFPR_f contribute most to PC2. They have some angle between them, so they are only weakly correlated. Finally, GNIpc has the least contribution to either PC - a more or less opposite result to the result from PCA with non-standardized data.

5.4 My interpretation of the PCs

The dimensions of human development: health, education, and standard of living, are represented in the human dataset by life expectancy LE, expected years of schooling EDS and gross national income per capita GNIpc, respectively. Combined with the dimensions driving gender inequality: reproductive health, empowerment and economic status of women, this dataset yields insight on the position of women and the human development costs of gender inequality in the 155 countries included. Reproductive health is represented in this dataset by maternal mortality ratio MMRand adolescent birth rates ABR, empowerment by female representation in parliament PR and proportion with secondary education SE_f, and economic status by the labor force participation rate LFPR_f.

Principal component PC1 (figure 5.3) explains more than half of the variation in the dataset. The variables contributing to it are strongly correlated. Three of these variables are related to health: life expectancy, maternal mortality, and adolescent births. And not surprisingly, life expectancy as a general population health measure “pulls” PC1 to an opposite direction from the other two variables that measure rather dishealth in the female population than health in general. Similarly, the strong correlation between the variables relating to education is to be expected. More interestingly, the education measures appear quite tightly related to life expectancy, the general population health measure.

5.5 MCA with ‘tea’ data

Multiple Correspondence Analysis (MCA) can be used to analyze the systematic patterns of variation with categorical data. It has some special features that make it mathematically different from PCA, but they both share a lot of things in common from a data analysis standpoint. The data should be in a dataframe with qualitative variables (factors) in the columns.

# load data
data("tea")

The data used here is included in FactoMineR package. The dataset comes from a questionnaire about tea consumption. 300 individuals were asked how they drink tea (18 questions), what are their product’s perception (12 questions) and some personal details (4 questions). The questionnaire is described in more detail by Husson, F., Le, S. and Pages, J. (2010). Exploratory Multivariate Analysis by Example Using R, Chapman and Hall.

Eigenvalues correspond to the amount of variation explained by each dimension. In my MCA, the first two dimensions explain no more than 23.6% of the variation.

It’s also possible to check how well the dimensions 1 and 2 represent the variable categories (i.e. factors by level).

# Color by cos2 values: quality of representation on the factor map
fviz_mca_var(mca, col.var = "cos2",
             gradient.cols = c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800", "#FC4E07"), 
             repel = TRUE, # Avoid text overlapping
             ggtheme = theme_minimal(),
             invisible = "quali.sup")

The closer to 1 (red color) the cos2 value is, the better the dimensions 1 and 2 represent each category. None of the categories are a perfect match (the highest cos values are 0.6) to either dimension. There are several categories poorly represented (cos2 < 0.1) by these dimension, therefore, the two-dimensional scatterplot should be interpreted with caution.

The scatterplot shows the relationships between variable categories. In the plot below, the active variables are colored red and supplementary variables green.

# visualize variable categories
fviz_mca_var(mca, 
             repel = TRUE, # to avoid text overlapping
             ggtheme = theme_minimal())

Variable categories with a similar profile are grouped together, e.g. “unpackaged” and “p_upscale”. Negatively correlated variable categories are positioned on opposite sides of the plot origin, e.g. . “p_unknown” and “other”. The distance between category points and the origin measures the quality of the variable category, i.e. category points that are away from the origin (e.g. “p_unknown”) are well represented on the factor map.

It’s also interesting to look at the contribution of each variable to dimensions 1 and 2.

# Contributions to dimension 1

# Contributions to dimension 2
fviz_contrib(mca, choice = "var", axes = 2, top = 10)

The variable categories with the larger values, contribute the most to the definition of the dimensions. Categories “p_upscale” and “unpackaged” contribute most to dimension 1, and categories “p_variable” and “tea bag+unpackaged” to dimension 2. These contributions can be visualized on a scatterplot by highlighting the categories with a color gradient.
